{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/hearing-loss-in-adults/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"6f91987e-3ad1-50d2-9fa8-cb374f1fea65","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 77242c2e-ab4c-45b9-9c9a-aa0600bd1314 --><h1>Hearing loss in adults: Summary</h1><!-- end field 77242c2e-ab4c-45b9-9c9a-aa0600bd1314 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b17df688-c1b0-483c-8f76-aa0600bd1314 --><!-- begin field b7ed593e-8e69-49de-ac78-aa0600bd1314 --><ul><li>Hearing loss is common and can occur at any age — depending on the underlying cause it can be temporary or permanent; of sudden onset or slowly progressive.<ul><li>Conductive hearing loss occurs due to abnormalities of the outer or middle ear which impair sound wave conduction to the cochlea in the inner ear.</li><li>Sensorineural hearing loss occurs due to abnormalities in the cochlea, auditory nerve or other structures in the neural pathway from the inner ear to the auditory cortex.</li></ul></li><li>Classification of hearing loss as mild, moderate, severe or profound is based on the quietest sound (in decibels) which can be discerned on pure tone audiometry.</li><li>The most common causes of hearing loss are ageing and exposure to excessive noise. Other causes include a wide variety of genetic, systemic and infective conditions and exposure to ototoxins.</li><li>Over 11 million people in the UK have hearing loss — around 900,000 people have severe or profound hearing loss.</li><li>Hearing loss can have a marked adverse effect on relationships, social engagement, employment and educational opportunities, quality of life and mental health.</li><li>Management of hearing loss in primary care involves:<ul><li>Treatment of causes such as impacted wax, acute ear infection (otitis externa or media) and middle ear effusion due to acute upper respiratory tract infection.</li><li>Consideration of the need for immediate, urgent or routine referral to an ENT specialist or emergency department.</li><li>Arrangement of audiological assessment where referral to ENT is not indicated.</li><li>Provision of support and information.</li></ul></li><li>Immediate referral (to be seen within 24 hours) to ENT or an emergency department should be arranged for:<ul><li>Sudden onset (over 3 days or less) unilateral or bilateral hearing loss occurring <em>within the past 30 days </em>which cannot be explained by external or middle ear causes.</li><li>Unilateral hearing loss associated with focal neurology.</li><li>Hearing loss associated with head or neck injury.</li><li>Otalgia and otorrhoea that has not responded to treatment within 72 hours in a person with immunosuppression.</li></ul></li><li>Urgent referral (to be seen within 2 weeks) to ENT or an audiovestibular medicine service should be arranged for:<ul><li>Sudden onset (over 3 days or less) unilateral or bilateral hearing loss which developed <em>more than 30 days ago</em> and cannot be explained by external or middle ear causes.</li><li>Rapidly progressive hearing loss (over 4–90 days) which cannot be explained by external or middle ear causes.</li><li>Suspected head or neck malignancy.</li></ul></li><li>Routine referral to ENT or audiovestibular medicine should be arranged for hearing loss (not explained by acute external or middle ear causes) which is:<ul><li>Unilateral or asymmetrical and of gradual onset.</li><li>Fluctuating and not associated with upper respiratory tract infection.</li><li>Associated with hyperacusis.</li><li>Associated with persistent unilateral, pulsatile, significantly changed or distressing tinnitus.</li><li>Associated with persistent or recurrent vertigo.</li><li>Not thought to be age related.</li></ul></li><li>Referral to an audiology service (to screen for hearing loss) should be considered in adults with suspected or diagnosed cognitive impairment or learning disability.</li></ul><!-- end field b7ed593e-8e69-49de-ac78-aa0600bd1314 --><!-- end item b17df688-c1b0-483c-8f76-aa0600bd1314 -->","topic":{"id":"04ebfcd5-34b5-50ed-9f39-eb5d18a386dd","topicId":"2f4e8b5b-3e3c-4daf-95b5-aa0600bd0fb1","topicName":"Hearing loss in adults","slug":"hearing-loss-in-adults","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"6f91987e-3ad1-50d2-9fa8-cb374f1fea65","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"234d842b-e403-5767-84ee-5c7e01fd73df","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"1e784365-09cd-5406-9baa-82e13b39db65","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"976993cf-ed52-538c-895a-e817e69054b2","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"04b1ba81-cc05-5054-96b7-84655edba2ea","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"671eaddd-f19a-5497-80ac-f748bdc43b3d","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"c7d5b46b-876d-50e0-8276-483b363e0125","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"88c30095-2b11-5623-9e81-21310fab6825","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"adf2bb1c-e78f-56bd-8121-102e9f9a0930","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"a77c7d6a-9562-58e0-ae15-03ca7eb5b812","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"0beb5cf3-fc6b-5528-a22c-ef0cf3661bb2","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"9c5106bd-3635-56e5-ac21-ee0805439f64","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"73119727-f2c5-5c0b-a39d-f6445141c0cc","slug":"background-information","fullItemName":"Background information","subChapters":[{"id":"de978432-0e82-5250-8d99-a7326f43ee2f","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"9b0c2c88-d92e-51d5-9592-19705cb6fb81","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes"},{"id":"47659fd5-a835-50a9-9fe1-5d287561d806"